[4] Suspected, technology, funding

21 May 2015: Air France to resume flights to Ebola-hit Sierra Leone
http://www.travelmole.com/news_feature.php?news_id=2016800&c=setregÂ®ion=2
[Air France resumes services to Sierra Leone in June 2015, while British Airways' flights to the country remain suspended. Both carriers temporarily halted services to Sierra Leone in August 2014 following an outbreak of Ebola. British Airways also halted flights to Liberia.]

21 May 2015 Guinea: imams committed to Muslim rituals for Ebola victims
http://news.videonews.us/guinea-imams-committed-muslim-rituals-ebola-victims-2117845.html
[This includes washing of the dead body, unless the body is decomposing, in which case, water is sprinkled on the body.]

21 May 2015 Liberia: Ebola made us impotent
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505211343.html?viewall=1
[According to the spokesperson for the Armah Kiawu, survivors of the Ebola virus disease have experienced serious health complications, including impotence in males and lack of menstruation in females.]

19 May 2015 Liberia: Work to resume at Liberia hydro plant after Ebola outbreak
http://www.trust.org/item/20150519181946-r7lbd/
[Work on a hydropower project in Liberia is about to resume after the work was interrupted during the Ebola outbreak. The Mount Coffee dam on the River Paul in Montserrado County once powered 1/3rd of households in the West African country. The facility was left battered by Liberia's civil war in 1989-2003, and the project to rehabilitate the dam was stopped by the Ebola epidemic in Liberia.]

24 May 2015 Portugal: 4 more Portuguese Ebola specialists head for Guinea-Bissau
http://theportugalnews.com/news/four-more-portuguese-ebola-specialists-head-for-guinea-bissau/34873
[Following a request from WHO, the Portuguese health department is sending another 4 specialists both to help detect and prevent Ebola, and to expand the team already in the country.]

20 May 2015: Sierra Leone News -- Port Loko wants double lab tests on new Ebola cases
http://news.sl/drwebsite/publish/article_200527639.shtml
[The Northern District of Port Loko has demanded a 2nd laboratory test on every Ebola-positive case before final results are disseminated for public review.]

20 May 2015 Sierra Leone: WHO probing Italian's Africa infection
http://www.ansa.it/english/news/general_news/2015/05/20/who-probing-italians-africa-infection_bc653648-3735-4c0d-9700-ca6a3fd02df0.html
[The World Health Organization (WHO) reports it is looking into the manner of the initial infection of the Italian nurse who contracted the virus while working for NGO Emergency in Sierra Leone and is not investigating the patient management in Italy.]

21 May 2015 Sierra Leone: President urges more sensitization on the issue of pregnant girls
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505211367.html
[At State House on Wed 20 May 2015, during a stakeholders' meeting, President Ernest Bai Koroma expressed the need for more mobilization and sensitization of the people to get them to understand and accept the return of pregnant girls to school.]

Vaccines, drugs, technology, research
------------------
20 May 2015: Nigeria, 7 others to begin Ebola vaccine trial
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505201591.html?viewall=1
[Vaccine trials will soon start in 8 African nations: Liberia, Nigeria, Sierra Leone, Guinea, Cameroon, Ghana, Mali and Senegal.]

20 May 2015 USA: USAMRIID monitors Ebola's evolution in Liberia
http://www.fredericknewspost.com/news/health/research/usamriid-monitors-ebola-s-evolution-in-liberia/article_a885a9a3-2632-5363-bf01-3e19a0c4f0bc.html
[According to the U.S. Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases spokesperson, the USAMRIID has created the 1st center to monitor genetic changes in the Ebola virus. Researchers at the new facility can monitor changes in the virus within a week of sample collection. Previous efforts to sequence the Makona strain of Ebola virus were slowed by the process of sending samples to the U.S. The center will be housed in the Liberian Institute for Biomedical Research. Liberian personnel were trained to run the center since USAMRIID staff will rotate between Fort Detrick and Liberia.]

21 May 2015 USA (Connecticut): Ebola scare clears building, proves false
http://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/ebola_scare_clears_building_proves_false/

Regional
---
20 May 2015 West Africa: UN health agency responds to Ebola spike by deploying team on Guinea border with Guinea-Bissau
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505211314.html?viewall=1
[In response to a "substantial increase" in the weekly total number of Ebola cases in Guinea and Sierra Leone, the World Health Organization sent a response team to the border with Guinea Bissau because of its proximity to a recent cluster of cases in a neighboring Guinean prefecture.]

21 May 2015 UK, Liberia: Defence scientists support efforts to defeat Ebola
https://www.gov.uk/government/news/defence-scientists-support-efforts-to-defeat-ebola
[The Ministry of Defence's Defence Science and Technology Laboratory (Dstl) has an active research program on Ebola and has developed expertise in handling and manipulating the virus (Eurosurveillance, Volume 20, Issue 12, 26 Mar 2015).]

Vaccines, drugs, research
--------------
21 May 2015 Ghana: Ebola vaccine trial hits Hohoe; GH-cedi 200 [USD 50] and phones for participants
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=359067&channel=A3
[Students of the Hohoe Midwifery Training College in the Volta region are concerned following a decision to use them as testing subjects for an upcoming Ebola drug (brincidofovir) trial in Ghana. Brincidofovir is an antiviral and one of several experimental drugs administered to a small number of patients to treat Ebola virus disease during the 2014 outbreak. It is reported that officials of the University of Health and Allied Sciences in Ho are spearheading the trial. The trial was successfully conducted on animals, and was safe. In addition to the USD 50 and phones, trial subjects will also receive other compensations, such as transport fares among others, depending on how the trial goes.]

22 May 2015 Guinea: sees Ebola spike as families transport bodies on public buses
http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/nationworld/ct-guinea-ebola-20150522-story.html
[According to authorities, the relatives of Ebola victims are transporting victims' bodies on public transportation in Guinea, seating the corpses upright between other passengers to avoid health controls. This practice is contributing to the spread of Ebola virus disease in Guinea.]

21 May 2015 Liberia: Post Ebola -- Liberian bush meat sellers want ban lifted
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505220586.html?viewall=1

22 May 2015 Liberia: Confederation of African Football clears Liberia to host home matches after Ebola ban -- Guinea, Sierra Leone remain banned
http://ghanasoccernet.com/caf-clears-liberia-to-host-home-matches-after-ebola-ban-guinea-sierra-leone-remain-banned/#sthash.HqNRLCtQ.dpuf

22 May 2015 UK: George Galloway was sent "Ebola package" forcing police to quarantine staff in his office
http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/george-galloway-sent-ebola-package-5744921
[The former Bradford West Minister of Parliament was sent a suspicious parcel, which it was claimed had a handkerchief which was "infected by Ebola." Staff were quarantined at the office in West Yorkshire while police and experts tested the suspicious parcel, according to Mr. Galloway. West Yorkshire Police said the package, said to contain a "hazardous substance," did not pose any risk (in which case, how could it have been hazardous? - Mod.JW).]

22 May 2015 UK: Defense scientists support efforts to defeat Ebola
http://www.wired-gov.net/wg/news.nsf/articles/Defence+scientists+support+efforts+to+defeat+Ebola+22052015131548
[Ministry of Defense scientists have been working with industry and government partners to help combat the Ebola outbreak in Sierra Leone.]

